<div class="container" id="datamod">
<p style="display: flex; justify-content: left;font-weight:bold;"> <font size="5px" color="#23bacf"><u>Data Modelling</u></font></p>

<div class="row" style="display: flex; justify-content: center;margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px;">
<div class="col-lg-12 bg-default bg-white py-0" style="margin-bottom:10px;margin-top:10px;;">
<h4 style="color:grey;">The application is expected to generate data primarily from orders, video calls, logistics, payments and marketing. 
The data belonging to the entities are of a much smaller proportion and static compared to the transactional & customer feedback data, assuming the merchant has an active presence online and is currently handling considerable volumes of customer transactions.
<br/><br/>There are going to be numerous relations connecting the various entities and functional pieces that represent a process or an event.
We are not following all the conventional practices of database design but ensuring that our data is going to be normalized to the highest degree. 
This is mainly to utilize the latest developments in application architecture that will help us 
in making the individual parts loosely coupled unless they are bundled in order to provide a useful real-world functionality.
</h4>

</div>
